{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411399"},"attributes":{"position":12,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13745"}},"bookmark":{"data":{"type":"bookmarks","id":"1210300"}}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476456"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:47:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13745"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.13,0.48,0.19,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104499"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6364"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86826"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43916"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104499"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her mother with a six-month history of recurrent central abdominal pain. The episodes occur every one to two months, last for several hours, and are associated with nausea, pallor, and fatigue. Between episodes she is well. She has no vomiting, diarrhoea, or weight loss. Her medical history includes migraine headaches. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Previous investigations for the same symptoms including coeliac serology, full blood count, LFT\u0027s, CRP and abdominal ultrasound have been normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecal calprotectin","Upper endoscopy and colonoscopy","No further investigations","Urea breath test","Urine culture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical presentation is consistent with abdominal migraine, which is characterised by stereotypical episodes of periumbilical pain lasting 1-72 hours with associated vasomotor symptoms such as pallor, and complete resolution of symptoms between attacks. The diagnosis can be made clinically based on the ICHD-3 diagnostic criteria in patients with normal physical examination and growth, after exclusion of other disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial investigations for recurrent abdominal pain typically include coeliac serology to exclude coeliac disease, and inflammatory markers such as CRP to screen for inflammatory conditions. In a well-appearing child with normal examination and preliminary investigations, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno further investigations\u003C/strong\u003E are required to diagnose abdominal migraine if the clinical criteria are met.  Focus instead can then turn to management strategies such as avoiding triggers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal calprotectin\u003C/strong\u003E is a marker of intestinal inflammation that may be elevated in inflammatory bowel disease. It is not routinely indicated in the evaluation of abdominal migraine. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic evaluation\u003C/strong\u003E is not required unless alarm symptoms are present or the diagnosis is uncertain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose Helicobacter pylori infection, which can cause peptic ulcer disease. This would not be indicated in a patient with episodic symptoms and complete resolution between episodes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine culture\u003C/strong\u003E is useful to exclude urinary tract infection as a cause of abdominal pain, but the stereotyped episodic nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms is more consistent with abdominal migraine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal migraine is a functional gastrointestinal disorder characterised by recurrent episodes of periumbilical pain and associated vasomotor symptoms.","Diagnosis of abdominal migraine is based on clinical criteria after exclusion of organic pathology.","Coeliac disease should be excluded in patients with recurrent abdominal pain."],"references":["ICHD Abdominal Migrane. In: IHS Classification [online]. Available at: https://ichd-3.org/1-migraine/1-6-episodic-syndromes-that-may-be-associated-with-migraine/1-6-1-recurrent-gastrointestinal-disturbance/1-6-1-2-abdominal-migraine/","Azmy DJ, Qualia CM. Review of Abdominal Migraine in Children. Gastroenterol Hepatol (N Y). 2020 Dec;16(12):632-639. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8132691/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86826"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86826"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T12:19:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T12:19:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6364"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"